5519
800 N Point St
San Francisco, CA 94109
(415) 749-2060

WOW O WOW. can I rave about this restaurant anymore? YES! My man surprised me for our 4th anniversary with a wonderful dining experience here. service - impeccable food - orgasmic presentation - beautiful from the moment we walked in to the seconds before we left, we were treated like royalty. we ordered the 5 course tasting menu with wine pairing...A MUST!!! the wine is superb by itself but with the food, it was divine! we got a very nice booth, someone isolated from the other tables, so we can still see the whole of the restaurant but still have our privacy to enjoy our anniversary dinner. what a wonderful dining experience that I am rooting we will be back at least once to twice a year.

If you're like me, then you don't go to places as fancy as Gary Danko all too often. It's a once-in-a-great-long-while sort of experience. It requires planning. It requires organization. You have to work to get reservations, to round up the right ground of people; you get your expectations way, way up for a memorable night. Thing is, there are lots of Michelin-star caliber restaurants in the Bay Area. I.e., you've got a lot of choices for your Special Night. And so the question is: which restaurants are worth going through this ordeal for? Which ones are worth your time and dollar? And is Gary Danko one of them? The answer to that last question is a resounding Maybe. I think the food is good. Good enough to warrant the price? I don't know about that. That said, the service and atmosphere are indeed there. So if you're the sort of person who believe that a memorable dinner is as much about the food as it is the atmosphere and the company you're with and the expectations and attitude you take into it, then I think you're good; I think Gary Danko will be a good choice for you. If you want THE BEST MEAL OF YOUR LIFE, then you might want to keep looking.

Everyone's covered everything you need to know about it. So my quick tips are: Gotta go 5 courses (the difference in between 3-4-5 are not that much anyways), mix and match your courses tho to make it right for you, get the side table flambe dessert for $6 extra (dont be cheap cuz you're already spending dough), bring your own wine and pay for the corking fee, sit down and have one of the most amazing meals in your entire life. The service is impeccable as well. The somaliers and the wait staff all know what they're doing and carry themselves with pride working for such a prestigious restaurant.

I'd been meaning to try this place for years and finally got around to it just before moving out of the bay. Got a reservation a few weeks ahead of time, which we were happy about. We did have to wait at the bar for about 15 minutes before getting seated, but it wasn't that bad. The vibe inside was way more old school than I imagined. Gaudy flower arrangements everywhere. Weird, but somehow fitting. I didn't dislike it, but can't say that I particularly enjoyed it either. The food did live up to the hype. I liked that it wasn't just a fixe prix menu where everything was chosen, but you could actually choose what you wanted from the menu. Everything we got was really great, but we ended up so full that we couldn't eat the little desserts they brought out at the end. They packed them to go, and even gave us a little cake to take home with us. Cute idea. Overall, I think it was worth it, even though it wasn't the best meal I've ever had in my life. I feel like this place is a must-try for bay area residents, but maybe only once.

I don't know of any other Michelin-starred restaurant that will let you choose 5 meat entree courses for your entire prix fixe meal. Just meat, no appetizers nor desserts. My brother and I shared our meat choices with our girlfriends, who went both for a lighter choice: the curried carrot soup - Amuse Bouche and the seared sea scallops (delicious they both said). Because it was my birthday, the server brought me a freebie dessert, a chocolate mousse cake, which I couldn't taste, so full I was!

I am always a big fan of great customer service (and just plain old being nice to your fellow neighbor, stranger, surroundings.) So when the staff at Gary Danko made me and my husband feel welcomed and appreciated from beginning to end, I knew that this dining experience had to be praised and shared. The second we entered the restaurant, we were greeted by a wonderful hostess who took our coats and had a server come over to take our drink order while we waited a few minutes for our table. Once our table was ready, a server took our drinks from our hands and placed them on a tray as she walked alongside us to our table. Immediately I knew that we would be taken care of. You are pretty much pampered the rest of the night. The food was incredible. Each dish came out with just the right amount of spacing in between them. Enough to savor the dish before, enjoy a sip of wine, and get excited for the next dish. It was like clockwork. Never feeling rushed and never feeling like you are forgotten. After the end of our meal, when we felt ready to get up and go, everything was ready and waiting for us. We walked to the front of the restaurant, where the hostess magically appeared with our coats and our car was waiting for us right out front with the parking attendant. Again, the timing here was perfect. He asked about our dinner and helped me into my seat. My husband and I continue to talk about the amazing time we had here at Gary Danko. Yes, good food is very important at any restaurant, but so is treating others kindly and this place did them both exceptionally well.

Really do want to say 3.5 stars. Too clearly, I walked in with expectations. After reading up that this place has a Michelin star, 4.5 Yelp stars, is stacked against French Laundry and La Folie and the like, I was REALLY excited. The six of us planned to visit about a month or so in advance for a Friday night at the end of August 2012 (yes! this is how long I thought about my review and why I just cannot give them 5 stars or even 4) Here's the main pro for this restaurant --- 3, 4, or 5 courses up to you and even in the order in which you'd like them --- Since we had 6 people, we were able to order a variety of dishes and share tastes -- someone with a big appetite even got 4 main courses and was stuffed ^_^ * Scallops (get this) * Branzino (avoid this) * Crispy farm egg (get this!!!) * Beef filet (get this, medium) * Lamb (get this) * Lobster Risotto (get this, just know it's "heavy") * Pork loin (get this) * Cheese (get this, do take the time to listen to descriptions if you don't already know what you'd like) * Thai Curry (get this, table was split on this) * Duck (get this) * Seared Ahi (avoid this) * Creme Brulee (avoid this, table was split on this) * Butter Cake (get this) * Chocolate souffle (get this -- although it doesn't beat Roy's or the Northbeach place I'm told) * Wine wine wine (ok you really should get wine or a drink with your food, even if it's just one glass) Probably due to the volume of seatings over time, this place does not feel as specially taken care of, if there were such a way to define a restaurant. Silverware is scuffed, service sometimes can feel impersonal although some servers really do pour themselves into the job, they don't provide steak knives (a medium-plus steak needs more than a butter knife esp. if it's crispy and comes with crunchy veggies), and there was a weird feel to the service since some of it was peer-training or a waitstaff paired with another who was assisting and learning at the same time. I guess that's all fine and really attention to detail/nit-picky, but this place isn't cheap and is supposed to exhibit an "enveloping, and intimate space" with "seamless" service as taken from their website -- felt at times that they were trying to move our large party along (our reservation was at ~2hrs before closing so I assume we were the last table seating for our particular table?). Another two misses were 1) a server's spill of a drink, ice and all, on the table and 2) pretty uneven distribution of chocolate sauce for one of the people at our table's souffles (two were ordered, the same sauce container was used which is totally fine, but after pouring the sauce in to one souffle, there was really barely a spoon or two for the second :( ... diner didn't mind much, but the detail is rather important). It's been nearly a year since my visit and I've finally posted the draft review sitting in my Yelp draft area. While looking at all the 4-5 star reviews, I really have to think I went on a pretty off-Friday night. Guess I'll need to go again to bump my review up ... looking forward to the next special occasion/excuse! ... :D

Went here for my 10 year anniversary dinner. Although food and service was great, I was disappointed they didn't do anything special to celebrate our anniversary so the evening just felt like any other. Food: -Wasn't a big fan of the foie gras everybody raves about. (Bf felt the same.) -Loved the branzini; the fennel purée with orange emulsion complemented it perfectly! I dream about that dish. -Quail was good--crispy & flavorful. -Lobster was good. If I come back, I'll be sure to try the soufflé. It looked decadent.

It's not often I give a place 5 stars but i felt Gary Dankos offers great food AND great value. A very rare combination. The tasting menu is very reasonably priced, especially considering you can mix and match your courses (such as 2 appetizers + 3 entrees or 1 appetizer + 3 entrees + 1 dessert). My problem with tasting menus is that i don't care for dessert and the dessert course always seems like a waste to me. I chose the following selection lobster risotto with tomato puree - really good, the risotto was not heavy and the tomato really offered a refreshing taste to the richness of the risotto lemongrass curry seafood - i'm always hesitant to order any kind of asian dish in a non asian restaurant but this time i'm glad i did. The curry had a very strong lemongrass flavor just the way i like it...the only thing that kept this dish from a perfect 10 is that i would have liked the consistency of the curry to be slightly thicker stuffed quail - i loved how the quail was stuffed with it's legs tied together just like a tiny thanksgiving turkey. the quail was tender and excellently flavored (although possibly slightly too salty) juniper crusted bison - i was slightly disappointed with this dish because when i read crusted i was thinking like a crunchy charred peppercorn type crust. But there wasn't really a crust of any sort at all. But they did cook the meat perfectly, was pretty juicy even though it's such a lean cut of meat. The service was also impeccable....above and beyond a lot of other more expensive restaurants i've been to. I would definitely recommend this place!

What an incredible dining experience! Food superb, service impeccable, I don't think I have anything remotely negative to share! I went with two friends, celebrating my birthday - how nice! To start they had an amuse bouche which was a cold cantaloupe soup with diced tomato and bacon - just about 2-3 spoons full - a perfect refreshing, summery start. My dining companion who has dined there frequently, in the past had enjoyed another amuse bouche of smoked salmon, crème fraiche and caviar on a buttery bilini...they nicely accommodated his special request. It was the perfect bite of incredible flavors! We each had many courses and shared, so it was wonderful to be able to enjoy and sample so many delicious dishes including: Seared ahi tuna with avocado, nori, enoki mushrooms in a lemon soy dressing (this was my favorite thing!) Pan seared scallops with mushroom and peas in a madeira sauce (amazing) Lemon pepper duck breast with duck hash, bacon braised endive and port roasted figs Risotto with rock shrimp, dungeness crab, tomato compote, shimeji mushrooms and corn Branzini with fennel puree, nicoise olives and saffron-orange emulsion Salad of black mission figs, arugula, fennel, gorgonzola dolce, and a pecan crostini Coconut thai curry with shrimp, calamari, lobster, scallops, candied peanuts and shiitake mushrooms Seared filet of beef with potato gnocchi, swiss chard and stilton butter melted on top For desserts we had the trio of sorbets - blackberry, peach and creme anglaise - each had a different little cookie - and the chocolate souffle with a creme anglaise sauce. They then brought out a complimentary chocolate fudge cake with a candle and happy birthday written on the plate which was nice. They also give everyone a "breakfast cake" to take home at the end of the meal to have the next day - a really nice lemon cake. What a nice touch. So, all in all, just a fantastic evening! I wish I could dine there every week!

Amazing food and experience!!! As a mom, my husband and I don't get to go out too often. So when we do, I want the best food for my time. Not only was every bite eye rolling good, but the service was impeccable! Each course was delivered to all 8 of our friends at the exact same time and we all had someone in our ears explaining what they were serving us. I kind of felt like royalty;)

I had a dinner date with my significant other and Gary Danko didn't disappoint me. From the time that we walked in, we were graciously greeted with smiling faces. Once seated, we had many waiters eagerly to serve us. Our main waiter was very friendly and professional and he has worked there 10 years and counting. When it comes to choosing your meals, we had many options, but we choose the 3- courses meal option for $76 dollars. The surprising thing is that we can choose any 3 we want, even from the entree sections. So between the two of us, we decided to try more of the entrees. So we ended up getting one appetizer, 4 entrees, and one dessert. The lobster salad was our starter. Fresh avocado with mixed green salad and grape fruits plus the tender half-lobster was a great start. We felt very healthy eating that lobster salad. The lobster was cook perfectly well. My partner and I also had the Thai coconut seafood dish and it was to our surprise, we loved it. The risotto was cooked in real coconut which enhanced its flavored. The seafood selections complemented well with the sauce they used. We also ended our appetizer with the sea bass dish. Normally I don't like seabass because of the fishy smell, but this one also is cook to perfection. Our main entree were the filet mignon and the lobster served with smashed potatoes. My partner said his filet mignon was done well, but the sauce could use a little more flavor. My lobster was cooked well, but the sauce with the smashed potatoes didn't go well with my palate. But over, our main entree were up to par with the rest. I love the dessert - the cheese cake, which was recommended by our waiter. I was full by then, but because I like the cheese cake that much, I ended finished all of it. Plus at the end of the meals, they brought us some extra dessert treats. Beside the attitude of the other diners (the richy-rich attitude), especially the table of four next to us, I try not to pay any attention to any of them. The restaurant actually is of small spaces, but the ambience was relaxing and beautifully decorated. We ended our meals with the kitchen tour, provided by once again our waiter. It's a good ending to our dinner date. I would come back here and bring some of my love one for all of the special occasion.

I like Gary Danko. I did not read yelp reviews before going in to GD so did not know that the 4 courses menu was quite a suicide mission. Bottom line - was trying to order too many meat dishes to make my money worth. I ordered the squab, the venison, the steak, and a tartar. What a joke! I overstuffed myself! And honestly I think if you order right, the 3 courses portion is still plentiful as you do get amuse bouche in between courses. The highlight of the meal was the bottle of 2005 Sloan Cabernet I took with me. It was hard to take bottles to Gary Danko as they won't allow bottles that are on their list, which they have quite an impressive list. Oh my gosh, the Sloan paired so well with the meat dishes! The bottle really opened up quite nicely at the end of the long dinner. So take a nice bottle of Cabernet and a nice Burgundy be the way to go.

Gary Danko's food is really good, but their service is what separates them from the rest. The ambiance is perfect for special occasions. Unlike other Michelin star restaurants, you actually get to pick which dishes you want to order rather than just getting a pre-fixe tasting menu, which is nice!

I'll be brief but honest. I'll probably not spend that kind of money elsewhere. The whole experience--staff, food, ambiance, beverage service, etc--were all beyond our expectations even with the knowledge of GD's reputation. An experience we will never forget and plan on having again!

Love this place, so great & so romantic. BF took me here for our anniversary and it was so sweet. He booked the reservations months in advance (and the only time left was 9PM...ok with me!) The courses were amazing and if you tell the staff it's an anniversary/special occasion, they bring out a special dessert plate. Came here for our wedding anniversary. What a special treat. Everybody was super attentive and welcoming. The food was delicious and of generous proportions. Great value too!

Amongst an obviously long list of great restaurants in San Francisco, Gary Danko tops my list of favorites. Have been there several times, and it has never failed to disappoint, often surpassing already high expectations. The interesting part about the menu is the flexibility: there are groups of appetizers and entrees (portion size between appetizer and entree for most items), cheese course, and desserts and you can choose from 3 to 5 course meals, with or without wine pairings. If you really like the meat section, you can choose a 3 course meal from that section, or choose a 5 course meal from the dessert section should you so desire. I highly recommend the wine pairing, as have tried wines I would not normally choose and found the pairing to be outstanding. The sommelier explains each pairing in detail and substitutes the wine with another if you don't care for it. We typically don't order a cheese course at other restaurants, but invariably get it here. It's not cheap and unless you know someone, you have to make reservations 2 months in advance, although the advance planning and the expense are certainly worth it. Also, for the amount and quality of the food, wine, service, and experience, I feel that the prices are more than reasonable. I've been to more expensive restaurants and felt gouged: never at Gary Danko. If you're going to SF, check it out at least once and enjoy!

Finally! Got myself to danko. This place doesn't need another high gloss review so I'll give u the bullet points for those that haven't been. Have u ever meet ur favorite celebrity? That's my feeling here. There is no way for GD to live up to the hype but they do a great job of trying. The service could not have been better. Each server brought their own knowledge to help us decide on the perfect menu. I do have to note the waiter that continually brought an onslaught of amazingly stuffed olives for our drinks! The menu was superbly executed. Some items good, others great. Of note was the best cheese cart I have ever tried. In summation, if u haven't, u should. Don't expect the world, just an amazing meal with amazing service in a great location. Another box checked on the bucket list....

I held off on writing this review b/c quite frankly, nobody needs another person saying how great this place is. It's every positive adj. you've read. It's the ideal spot for birthdays, anniversaries and just good old night out of fine dining. Tips: Call way ahead for the reservation and yes, believe the hype!

    * Chocolate souffle (get this -- although it doesn't beat Roy's or the Northbeach place I'm told)
    * Wine wine wine (ok you really should get wine or a drink with your food, even if it's just one glass)

    Probably due to the volume of seatings over time, this place does not feel as specially taken care of, if there were such a way to define a restaurant.  Silverware is scuffed, service sometimes can feel impersonal although some servers really do pour themselves into the job, they don't provide steak knives (a medium-plus steak needs more than a butter knife esp. if it's crispy and comes with crunchy veggies), and there was a weird feel to the service since some of it was peer-training or a waitstaff paired with another who was assisting and learning at the same time.  I guess that's all fine and really attention to detail/nit-picky, but this place isn't cheap and is supposed to exhibit an "enveloping, and intimate space" with "seamless" service as taken from their website -- felt at times that they were trying to move our large party along (our reservation was at ~2hrs before closing so I assume we were the last table seating for our particular table?).  Another two misses were 1) a server's spill of a drink, ice and all, on the table and 2) pretty uneven distribution of chocolate sauce for one of the people at our table's souffles (two were ordered, the same sauce container was used which is totally fine, but after pouring the sauce in to one souffle, there was really barely a spoon or two for the second :(  ... diner didn't mind much, but the detail is rather important).

    It's been nearly a year since my visit and I've finally posted the draft review sitting in my Yelp draft area.  While looking at all the 4-5 star reviews, I really have to think I went on a pretty off-Friday night.  Guess I'll need to go again to bump my review up ... looking forward to the next special occasion/excuse! ... :D

    1 check-in

    It's not often I give a place 5 stars but i felt Gary Dankos offers great food AND great value.  A very rare combination.

    The tasting menu is very reasonably priced,  especially considering you can mix and match your courses (such as 2 appetizers + 3 entrees  or 1 appetizer + 3 entrees + 1 dessert).  My problem with tasting menus is that i don't care for dessert and the dessert course always seems like a waste to me.

    I chose the following selection

    lobster risotto with tomato puree - really good, the risotto was not heavy and the tomato really offered a refreshing taste to the richness of the risotto

    lemongrass curry seafood - i'm always hesitant to order any kind of asian dish in a non asian restaurant but this time i'm glad i did.  The curry had a very strong lemongrass flavor just the way i like it...the only thing that kept this dish from a perfect 10 is that i would have liked the consistency of the curry to be slightly thicker

    stuffed quail - i loved how the quail was stuffed with it's legs tied together just like a tiny thanksgiving turkey.  the quail was tender and excellently flavored (although possibly slightly too salty)

    juniper crusted bison - i was slightly disappointed with this dish because when i read crusted i was thinking like a crunchy charred peppercorn type crust.  But there wasn't really a crust of any sort at all.  But they did cook the meat perfectly,  was pretty juicy even though it's such a lean cut of meat.

    The service was also impeccable....above and beyond a lot of other more expensive restaurants i've been to.  I would definitely recommend this place!

    I had a dinner date with my significant other and Gary Danko didn't disappoint me.  From the time that we walked in, we were graciously greeted with smiling faces.  Once seated, we had many waiters eagerly to serve us.  Our main waiter was very friendly and professional and he has worked there 10 years and counting.

    When it comes to choosing your meals, we had many options, but we choose the 3- courses meal option for $76 dollars.  The surprising thing is that we can choose any 3 we want, even from the entree sections.  So between the two of us, we decided to try more of the entrees.  So we ended up getting one appetizer, 4 entrees, and one dessert.

    The lobster salad was our starter.  Fresh avocado with mixed green salad and grape fruits plus the tender half-lobster was a great start.  We felt very healthy eating that lobster salad.  The lobster was cook perfectly well.  My partner and I also had the Thai coconut seafood dish and it was to our surprise, we loved it.  The risotto was cooked in real coconut which enhanced its flavored.  The seafood selections complemented well with the sauce they used.  We also ended our appetizer with the sea bass dish.  Normally I don't like seabass because of the fishy smell, but this one also is cook to perfection.

    Our main entree were the filet mignon and the lobster served with smashed potatoes.  My partner said his filet mignon was done well, but the sauce could use a little more flavor.  My lobster was cooked well, but the sauce with the smashed potatoes didn't go well with my palate.  But over, our main entree were up to par with the rest.  

    I love the dessert - the cheese cake, which was recommended by our waiter.  I was full by then, but because I like the cheese cake that much, I ended finished all of it.  Plus at the end of the meals, they brought us some extra dessert treats.  

    Beside the attitude of the other diners (the richy-rich attitude), especially the table of four next to us, I try not to pay any attention to any of them.  The restaurant actually is of small spaces, but the ambience was relaxing and beautifully decorated.

    We ended our meals with the kitchen tour, provided by once again our waiter.  It's a good ending to our dinner date.  I would come back here and bring some of my love one for all of the special occasion.

    1/25/2016

    10 photos

    Amongst an obviously long list of great restaurants in San Francisco, Gary Danko tops my list of favorites. Have been there several times, and it has never failed to disappoint, often surpassing already high expectations. The interesting part about the menu is the flexibility: there are groups of appetizers and entrees (portion size between appetizer and entree for most items), cheese course, and desserts and you can choose from 3 to 5 course meals, with or without wine pairings. If you really like the meat section, you can choose a 3 course meal from that section, or choose a 5 course meal from the dessert section should you so desire. I highly recommend the wine pairing, as have tried wines I would not normally choose and found the pairing to be outstanding. The sommelier explains each pairing in detail and substitutes the wine with another if you don't care for it. We typically don't order a cheese course at other restaurants, but invariably get it here. It's not cheap and unless you know someone, you have to make reservations 2 months in advance, although the advance planning and the expense are certainly worth it. Also, for the amount and quality of the food, wine, service, and experience, I feel that the prices are more than reasonable. I've been to more expensive restaurants and felt gouged: never at Gary Danko. If you're going to SF, check it out at least once and enjoy!
